### Feature 2: Section Loading & Structural Validation

**As a developer**, I want loading a named section of a configuration document to fail with a clear, stable reason whenever the document is structurally wrong, so misconfiguration is caught early and reported uniformly.

**Expected Behavior / Usage:**

A request names one section of a YAML configuration document. Loading rejects, with a single `error=<category>` line, each of the following: a configuration file that does not exist (`config_not_found`); a file whose parsed content is empty (`empty_config`); a file that is not valid YAML (`invalid_yaml`); a request for a section name that is not present in the document (`section_not_found`); a section that — after being overlaid on the shared inherited section — declares neither a `templates` list nor a `kubectl` list of deployable items (`missing_templates`); an empty section name (`empty_section`); and the reserved shared section name, which exists only to be inherited and is never deployable on its own (`reserved_section`). Each case prints exactly one error line.

**Test Cases:** `rcb_tests/public_test_cases/feature2_config_section_errors.json`

```json
{
    "description": "Loads a named section from a YAML configuration document and reports structural errors as neutral categories instead of raising. The loader rejects a missing configuration file, a file whose parsed content is empty, a file that is not valid YAML, a request for a section name that does not exist, and a section that (after being merged with the shared 'common' section) declares neither a 'templates' nor a 'kubectl' list of items to deploy. It also rejects an empty section name, and the reserved shared section name that exists only to be inherited and is never deployed on its own. Each case prints a single 'error=<category>' line identifying which rule was violated.",
    "cases": [
        {
            "input": {"op": "resolve", "section": "section", "no_config": true},
            "expected_output": "error=config_not_found\n"
        }
    ]
}
```

