### Feature 3: Variable Resolution & Placeholder Substitution

**As a developer**, I want section values to be assembled from a shared base, environment variables, and external files via inline placeholders, so I can avoid hardcoding environment-specific data and reuse fragments across sections.

**Expected Behavior / Usage:**

*3.1 Section Resolution with Placeholders — overlay on the shared section and expand `file=` and `env=` placeholders.*

Resolving a section overlays it on the shared inherited section and then expands string placeholders. A `file='<path>'` placeholder is replaced by the parsed YAML content of that file (yielding a nested structure). An `env='<NAME>'` placeholder is replaced by the value of that environment variable; literal text surrounding an `env=` placeholder is preserved, so placeholders may be concatenated with prefixes/suffixes or with one another. Section values override shared values, while mappings present in both are merged recursively. The fully resolved section is emitted as a JSON object with keys sorted.

**Test Cases:** `rcb_tests/public_test_cases/feature3_variable_resolution.json`

```json
{
    "description": "Resolves a configuration section by overlaying it on the shared 'common' section and expanding string placeholders. A placeholder of the form file='<path>' is replaced by the parsed YAML content of that file (yielding a nested mapping), and a placeholder of the form env='<NAME>' is replaced by the value of that environment variable; literal text surrounding an env placeholder is preserved so placeholders can be concatenated with prefixes/suffixes or with each other. Section values override common values, while mappings present in both are merged recursively. The output is the fully resolved section as a sorted JSON object.",
    "cases": [
        {
            "input": {
                "op": "resolve",
                "section": "test_dirs",
                "env": {"CUSTOM_ENV": "My value"},
                "aux_files": {"include.yaml": "---\nha_ha: \"included_var\"\n"},
                "config": "common:\n  my_var: my_value\n  my_file: \"{{ file='include.yaml' }}\"\n  my_env_var: \"{{ env='CUSTOM_ENV' }}\"\ntest_dirs:\n  dirs:\n    - dst: /tmp/test_directory1/\n  templates:\n    - template: template1.yaml.j2\n"
            },
            "expected_output": "{\n  \"dirs\": [\n    {\n      \"dst\": \"/tmp/test_directory1/\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"my_env_var\": \"My value\",\n  \"my_file\": {\n    \"ha_ha\": \"included_var\"\n  },\n  \"my_var\": \"my_value\",\n  \"templates\": [\n    {\n      \"template\": \"template1.yaml.j2\"\n    }\n  ]\n}"
        }
    ]
}
```

*3.2 Recursive Substitution over Arbitrary Structures — substitute placeholders in place across nested mappings, lists, and scalars.*

Given an arbitrary nested structure of mappings, lists, and scalars, walk it and substitute string placeholders in place while leaving non-string leaves untouched. Each string is scanned for an `env='<NAME>'` placeholder (replaced by the environment variable value; an unset variable expands to empty text in non-strict mode) and for a `file='<path>'` placeholder (replaced by the parsed YAML content of the referenced file). Numbers, booleans, and list ordering are preserved exactly, and a bare scalar passed in alone is returned unchanged. The transformed structure is emitted as a JSON object with keys sorted.

**Test Cases:** `rcb_tests/public_test_cases/feature3_recursive_substitution.json`

```json
{
    "description": "Walks an arbitrary nested structure (mappings, lists, and scalars) and substitutes string placeholders in place, leaving non-string leaves untouched. Each string is scanned for an env='<NAME>' placeholder that is replaced by the environment variable value (an unset variable expands to empty text in non-strict mode), and for a file='<path>' placeholder that is replaced by the parsed YAML content of the referenced file. Numbers, booleans, and list ordering are preserved exactly, and a bare scalar passed in alone is returned unchanged. Output is the transformed structure as sorted JSON.",
    "cases": [
        {
            "input": {
                "op": "update_context",
                "env": {"CUSTOM_ENV": "My value"},
                "aux_files": {"include.yaml": "---\nha_ha: \"included_var\"\n"},
                "context": {
                    "section1": {
                        "subsection1": {
                            "section1-key1": "value",
                            "section1-key2": 1,
                            "section1-key3": 0.1,
                            "section1-key4": [0, 1, 2, 3],
                            "section1-key5": "{{ env='CUSTOM_ENV' }}",
                            "section1-key6": "{{ file='include.yaml' }}",
                            "section1-key7": "{{ env='CUSTOM_ENV'}} = {{ env='CUSTOM_ENV' }}",
                            "section1-key8": "{{ env='NULL_VAR' }}-{{ env='CUSTOM_ENV' }}"
                        }
                    },
                    "section2": [{}, "var2", "var3", "{{ env='CUSTOM_ENV' }}", "{{ env='CUSTOM_ENV' }} = {{ env='CUSTOM_ENV' }}", "{{ env='NULL_VAR' }}-{{ env='CUSTOM_ENV' }}"],
                    "section3": [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]
                }
            },
            "expected_output": "{\n  \"section1\": {\n    \"subsection1\": {\n      \"section1-key1\": \"value\",\n      \"section1-key2\": 1,\n      \"section1-key3\": 0.1,\n      \"section1-key4\": [\n        0,\n        1,\n        2,\n        3\n      ],\n      \"section1-key5\": \"My value\",\n      \"section1-key6\": {\n        \"ha_ha\": \"included_var\"\n      },\n      \"section1-key7\": \"My value = My value\",\n      \"section1-key8\": \"-My value\"\n    }\n  },\n  \"section2\": [\n    {},\n    \"var2\",\n    \"var3\",\n    \"My value\",\n    \"My value = My value\",\n    \"-My value\"\n  ],\n  \"section3\": [\n    0,\n    1,\n    2,\n    3,\n    4\n  ]\n}"
        }
    ]
}
```

*3.3 Strict Unset-Variable Failure — in strict mode, an unset `env=` variable is a hard error.*

When strict environment resolution is enabled, expanding an `env='<NAME>'` placeholder for a variable that is not set is a hard error rather than substituting empty text. The rule applies to placeholders found directly in a section's values, to placeholders pulled in through a `file='<path>'` include, and through chains of nested includes. Each case enables strict mode with the referenced variable unset and prints `error=env_not_set` followed by a `var=<NAME>` line naming the offending variable.

**Test Cases:** `rcb_tests/public_test_cases/feature3_strict_env_unset.json`

```json
{
    "description": "When strict environment resolution is enabled, expanding a placeholder env='<NAME>' for an environment variable that is not set is treated as a hard error rather than substituting empty text. The rule applies to placeholders found directly in a section's values, in values pulled in through a file='<path>' include, and through chains of nested includes. Each case enables strict mode with the referenced variable unset and prints 'error=env_not_set' together with the offending variable name.",
    "cases": [
        {
            "input": {
                "op": "resolve",
                "section": "section_1",
                "strict": true,
                "config": "common:\n  k8s_namespace: namespace\nsection_1:\n  var: \"{{ env='SECTION1' }}\"\n  templates:\n    - template: template1.yaml.j2\n"
            },
            "expected_output": "error=env_not_set\nvar=SECTION1\n"
        }
    ]
}
```

*3.4 Cyclic Include Detection — abort instead of recursing forever.*

A `file='<path>'` placeholder may itself reference further files. If a value, directly or transitively through nested includes, references a file already visited on the current include path, resolution aborts instead of recursing forever. The case wires two include files that reference each other and prints `error=include_loop`.

**Test Cases:** `rcb_tests/public_test_cases/feature3_include_loop.json`

```json
{
    "description": "Detects a cyclic file='<path>' include chain while resolving a section and aborts instead of recursing forever. A value that, directly or transitively through nested includes, references a file that has already been visited on the current include path is rejected. The case wires two include files that reference each other and prints 'error=include_loop'.",
    "cases": [
        {
            "input": {
                "op": "resolve",
                "section": "section_3",
                "aux_files": {
                    "incorrect_include.yaml": "\n---\nincluded_file: \"{{ file='incorrect_include2.yaml' }}\"\n",
                    "incorrect_include2.yaml": "\n---\nincluded_file: \"{{ file='incorrect_include.yaml' }}\"\n"
                },
                "config": "common:\n  k8s_namespace: namespace\nsection_3:\n  var: \"{{ file='incorrect_include.yaml' }}\"\n  templates:\n    - template: template1.yaml.j2\n"
            },
            "expected_output": "error=include_loop\n"
        }
    ]
}
```

*3.5 Root Variable Name Validation — reject dashes in top-level keys.*

Root-level variable names in a resolved section must contain no dashes, because dashes are not legal identifiers for the templating step. Only top-level keys are checked; dashes nested inside values are permitted. A section whose merged root keys include one or more dashed names is rejected with `error=root_dashes` followed by a `vars=<names>` line listing the offending names in sorted order; a section whose dashes appear only in nested values resolves successfully to a sorted JSON object.

**Test Cases:** `rcb_tests/public_test_cases/feature3_root_dashes.json`

```json
{
    "description": "Validates that root-level variable names in a resolved section contain no dashes, because dashes are not legal identifiers for templating. Only top-level keys are checked; dashes nested inside mapping values are permitted. A section whose merged root keys include one or more dashed names is rejected with 'error=root_dashes' followed by the offending names in sorted order, while a section whose dashes appear only in nested values resolves successfully to a sorted JSON object.",
    "cases": [
        {
            "input": {
                "op": "resolve",
                "section": "not_allowed",
                "aux_files": {"include.yaml": "---\nha_ha: \"included_var\"\n"},
                "config": "common:\n  my_file: \"{{ file='include.yaml' }}\"\n  k8s_namespace: namespace\n  templates:\n    - template: template1.yaml.j2\nnot_allowed:\n  my-var: my_value\n  my-var-with-dashes: not allowed\n"
            },
            "expected_output": "error=root_dashes\nvars=my-var, my-var-with-dashes\n"
        }
    ]
}
```

