### Feature 5: Template Tag Selection

**As a developer**, I want to attach tags to template items and filter which ones are produced, so I can render a subset of a deployment (for example, only the database, or everything except the cron jobs) from the same configuration.

**Expected Behavior / Usage:**

*5.1 Tag-Based Inclusion Decision — allow-list and skip-list semantics.*

Decide whether a template that carries a set of tags should be included, given an optional allow-list (`only`) and an optional skip-list (`skip`). The template is excluded when an allow-list is given and the template shares no tag with it; excluded when a skip-list is given and the template shares any tag with it; otherwise included. With no lists given the template is always included, and these rules also hold when the template has no tags at all. Each evaluation prints `[a specific boolean result for tag matching in exclude logic]` or `[a specific boolean result for tag matching in exclude logic]` in order.

**Test Cases:** `rcb_tests/public_test_cases/feature5_evaluate_tags.json`

```json
{
    "description": "Decides whether a template that carries a set of tags should be included given an optional allow-list ('only') and an optional skip-list ('skip'). A template is excluded when an allow-list is given and the template shares no tag with it, and excluded when a skip-list is given and the template shares any tag with it; otherwise it is included. When no lists are given the template is always included, and these rules also hold when the template has no tags at all. Each evaluation prints a '[a specific boolean result for tag matching in exclude logic]' or '[a specific boolean result for tag matching in exclude logic]' line in order.",
    "cases": [
        {
            "input": {
                "op": "eval_tags",
                "evaluations": [
                    {"tags": ["tag1", "tag2", "tag3"], "only": ["tag1"], "skip": null},
                    {"tags": ["tag1", "tag2", "tag3"], "only": ["tag4"], "skip": null},
                    {"tags": ["tag1", "tag2", "tag3"], "only": ["tag1"], "skip": ["tag1"]},
                    {"tags": ["tag1", "tag2", "tag3"], "only": null, "skip": ["tag1"]},
                    {"tags": ["tag1", "tag2", "tag3"], "only": null, "skip": ["tag4"]},
                    {"tags": [], "only": ["tag4"], "skip": null},
                    {"tags": [], "only": null, "skip": ["tag4"]}
                ]
            },
            "expected_output": "[a specific boolean result for tag matching in exclude logic]\n[a specific boolean result for tag matching in exclude logic]\n[a specific boolean result for tag matching in exclude logic]\n[a specific boolean result for tag matching in exclude logic]\n[a specific boolean result for tag matching in exclude logic]\n[a specific boolean result for tag matching in exclude logic]\n[a specific boolean result for tag matching in exclude logic]\n"
        }
    ]
}
```

*5.2 Tag Normalization — accept list or comma-separated string, reject other types.*

Normalize the tags attached to a template item into a set. Tags provided as a list become the set of distinct entries; tags provided as a single comma-separated string are split on commas into a set; a one-element list and a single bare string each yield a single-tag set. Supplying tags of any other type is rejected with `error=unexpected_tags_type`. Each parsed result prints a `tags=` line with the members in sorted, comma-separated order.

